    en: "A NY patient with the capacity to make medical decisions has the right to leave a hospital at any time, even when the doctors recommend staying. The right comes from the broader right to refuse medical treatment and is supported by 10 NYCRR 405.7, the hospital patient bill of rights regulation under NY Public Health Law section 2803. The hospital usually asks the patient to sign an Against Medical Advice (AMA) form acknowledging the discussion of risks, but a patient cannot be physically restrained from leaving simply for refusing to sign. Common myths: insurance does NOT automatically refuse to pay for an AMA discharge — most plans cover the care given before the patient left. Limited exceptions where the patient cannot leave include mental-health emergency holds, contagious-disease isolation orders, and active criminal custody."
