    en: "A Rochester man was admitted to a Monroe County hospital for a heart catheterization. The procedure went well and the medical team recommended an additional 24 hours of monitoring. He needed to be home for his disabled wife who relied on him for daily care. He told the team he wanted to leave. The team explained the risks of early discharge, including possible bleeding from the catheterization site and possible heart-rhythm issues, and asked him to sign an AMA form. He read the form carefully and signed. He asked for a written summary of his diagnosis, the medications to take at home, the warning signs to watch for, and the follow-up appointment to schedule with his cardiologist. The discharge planner provided all of these. He was home that evening. His insurance paid for the hospital stay and the catheterization without difficulty — the AMA discharge had no effect on coverage. He attended the cardiology follow-up the next week and continued his recovery without complications."
